Date: Fri, 21 Jul 2000 00:18:12 -0400 (EDT)
From: Greg Folkers <GFOLKERS@niaid.nih.gov>
Source: Internet Mail Service (5.5.2650.21), Thurs, Jul 20 5:51 PM ET [edited

NY Rules Out West Nile Virus in Man's Death
---------------------------------------------

A man whose death raised concerns that he might have been infected with the
mosquito-borne [West Nile virus that killed seven people in the New York
area last year did not have the virus after all, officials said on
Thursday. New York City Health Commissioner Neal Cohen said at a news
conference that blood tests on the man were negative for the brain-swelling
West Nile virus, which had never been detected in the Western Hemisphere
until last year and has returned to the region this year in
mosquitoes and birds.

"Tests were done [for a variety of viruses and for West Nile virus, two
blood samples taken on two separate days, and they turned up absolutely
negative," stated Cohen, who said the definitive cause of the man's death
was not yet known.
Cohen said the 71-year-old man, who was visiting the city borough of Staten
Island from South Carolina when he died Wednesday morning, had other serious
health conditions. His death coincided with the discovery on Staten Island
of two dead birds infected with the West Nile Virus, prompting health
authorities to do precautionary testing. The birds were found in early July
and in further evidence that the virus survived the winter, mosquitoes in
the northern and eastern suburbs were also found to have been infected. The
virus is spread to humans by mosquitoes that have fed off infected birds. At
its worst, it can cause potentially deadly brain diseases such as
encephalitis (inflammation of the brain), or meningitis (inflammation of the
lining of the brain and spinal cord).

The elderly and children are particularly vulnerable. Last year, seven
people died and 62 others were sickened by the virus in the New York region.
US health authorities still do not know how the virus, named after the
region in Uganda where it was first detected in 1937, was introduced to the
New York area. It could have been from an infected bird that was imported or
an infected person returning from a country in Africa, southwestern Asia or
the Middle East, where the virus is common.

