Date: Fri, 21 Jul 2000 21:20:08 -0400
From: George A. Robertson <grobertson@rcn.com> [edited

Spraying Set for Staten Island and Queens After Discovery of More Dead Birds
-----------------------------------------
The city's battle against West Nile Virus heated up on two fronts Friday.
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced Friday that the city will embark on another
round of ground spraying after three more dead birds tested positive for the
virus: two on Staten Island and the other in the Little Neck/Douglaston
areas of Queens.
Spraying in Little Neck and Douglaston and virtually all of Staten Island is
set for Monday. However, the mayor says state and federal agencies are
restricting the city's ability to spray all the affected areas. The agencies
are not allowing the city to spray in the wetlands. Even though city
officials admit chemicals would kill some plants and wildlife, they say
people's lives should come first. "We're facing the risk of an outbreak of
West Nile Virus which has potential to end life, particularly in vulnerable
people, so we feel that we would like the state and federal government to
give a reconsideration to the balance in order to stem the tide of what
could be a very unacceptable outbreak," says Health Commissioner Neal Cohen.
Mayor Giuliani says he plans to speak with Governor George Pataki in the
hopes of winning his support.
The National Park Service says it isn't against the city spraying on Staten
Island, but it says the salt marshes at Jamaica Bay in Queens [are
off-limits
because it isn't a natural breeding ground for the virus-carrying mosquitos.
The state says it is trying to work with the city, but adds federal law
prohibits spraying pesticides that kill adult mosquitos in wetland areas.
The West Nile Virus killed seven people in the city last summer.
