[3
Date: Fri, 21 Jul 2000 14:36:11 GMT
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: UPI, Thurs, 20 Jul 2000 12:18 (ET) [edited

Deadly new mosquito discovered in Massachusetts
-----------------------------------------------
A new species of an Asian mosquito that can carry the dreaded West Nile
virus has been discovered for the first time in Massachusetts.
Entomologists found the mosquito, scientifically known as _Aedes
japonicus_, in a special trap set in Fitchburg, an industrial city
northwest of Boston. Near the trap they also uncovered a pool of the
mosquito larvae in standing water.

The discovery of a third type of mosquito capable of infecting people has
raised fears in the state as swarms of the tenacious insects have invaded
New England communities in reportedly greater numbers than in the past. Some
residents have given up sitting on their decks at night for fear of being
bitten. And towns wrestle with whether to spray or not to spray.Although the
Fitchburg mosquito was this week pronounced free of the virus, health
officials are taking no chances. They have stepped up their testing of
mosquitoes and dead birds that have succumbed to insect bites. They are also
alerting doctors throughout the state to the potential menace in their midst
and beseeching them to be vigilant in reporting adverse symptoms among their
patients, such as severe headache, stiff neck, seizures. The virus can cause
encephalitis, an acute inflammation in the brain, and lead to death.
The West Nile virus first appeared in the United States last year, infecting
68 people in New York, seven of whom died. The killer then was a common
species of mosquito, the _Culex pipiens_,which is typically a night flyer. A
second species, _Aedes vixens_, capable of carrying the virus, also prefers
night life. What makes the newly discovered _Aedes japonicus_ more
threatening is its preference for daytime activity, making it more difficult
to control. Experts believe the species entered the United States from Asia
in used tires shipments. State officials ear more species of mosquitoes
could soon be carrying the virus."This is only a precursor for more
mosquitoes to become vectors" to transmit the disease, Kenneth R.
Courtemanche, superintendent of the Central Massachusetts Mosquito Control
Project, told Thursday's Worcester Telegram.The control unit is advising
residents to refrain from hanging containers in their back yards and to make
sure house gutters are clean. Following last year's outbreak, Massachusetts
was one of 21 states along the East Coast that initiated a wide-scale effort
to destroy the insects. It put larvicide and briquettes in catch basins and
drains and ground sprayed parks and areas where mosquitoes hatched. It
expects to continue such activities and will respond to requests from cities
and towns seeking further aid.
