Date: Fri, 21 Jul 2000 17:35:08 -0400
From: Turell, Michael J Dr USAMRIID <Michael.Turell@DET.AMEDD.ARMY.MIL>

Comment on the potential of _Aedes japonicus_ to transmit West Nile virus
---------------------------------------------------
The recent detection of West Nile (WN) virus in _Aedes japonicus_ mosquitoes
from New York raised the question of the potential of this species to
transmit WN virus by bite. As part of our evaluation of potential vectors of
WN virus we tested both _Aedes japonicus_ and _Culex pipiens_. _Aedes
japonicus_ was a significantly more efficient laboratory vector of WN virus
than was _Culex pipiens_, with transmission rates of 64 and 21%,
respectively, for the two species after feeding on a chicken with a viremia
of about 10^7 plaque-forming units of virus per ml of blood. HOWEVER, the
ability to transmit a virus in the laboratory is just one factor in
determining its vectorial capacity. Of greater importance are host-feeding
preference, population density, and survival relative to the extrinsic
incubation period. Unfortunately, too little is known about this potentially
important vector, and studies need to be conducted to determine these
important parameters.
A manuscript describing the results of our vector competence studies on
these and other potential vectors of WN virus has been submitted for
publication to the Journal of Medical Entomology.
Michael J. Turell
Research Entomologist
Virology Division, USAMRIID
<Michael.Turell@DET.AMEDD.ARMY.MIL>
